tholic schools promote the development of social capital—the social networks and mutual trust that form the foundation of safe and cohesive communities. Drawing on data from the Project on Human Development in Chicago Neighborhoods and crime reports collected at the police beat or census tract level in Chicago, Philadelphia, and Los Angeles, Margaret F. Brinig and Nicole Stelle Garnett demonstrate that the loss of Catholic schools triggers disorder, crime, and an overall decline in community cohesiveness, and suggest that new charter schools fail to fill the gaps left behind. This book shows that the closing of Catholic schools harms the very communities they were created to bring together and serve, and it will have vital implications for both education and policing policy debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCatholic schoolsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCharter schoolszUnited States. 0aCommunity schoolszUnited States. 0aSchool choicezUnited States. 0aSchool closingsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  acatholic school, catholicism, catholics, christianity, christian community, law, cities, urban policy, educational studies, american culture, united states of america, elementary education, secondary schools, public learning, government regulations, social capital, networks, trust, project on human development in chicago neighborhoods, crime reports, police work, policing, charter, closures.1 aGarnett, Nicole Stelle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022612200740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226122144